[4] Argentina
Date: April 07, 2006
From: Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: 24 Horas, not ias, Chile. 7 Apr 2006 [Translated by JGM, edited]
<http://www.24horas.cl/detalle.aspx?IdC=199175&IdS=1>

The Argentinian Ministry of Health confirmed today the detection of 25
dengue fever cases in Misiones Province, which borders Brazil and Paraguay,
where the disease has also been detected.
"In addition to the 25 confirmed cases, another 13 suspected cases have
been detected, which are currently under study in order to rule out dengue
fever," announced the Health Ministry in a press release.
The outbreak is located in "Los Trabajadores" neighborhood in Puerto
Iguazu, a northern Argentinian city (Misiones Province), 1.615 km north of
Buenos Aires, and near Foz de Iguazu (Brazil) and Ciudad del Este
(Paraguay), in the area nearby the famous Iguazu cataracts.
Most affected persons presented with fever, headache, muscle and joint
pain, which are typical symptoms of dengue fever.
The Argentinian Ministry of Health sent technical personnel and specialized
equipment to the affected area in order to perform insecticide spraying
aiming to eliminate adults and larvae of the mosquito vector _Aedes aegypti_.
Authorities are keeping watch for persons with fever in the surrounding
areas, in order to determine whether they are infected with the dengue
fever virus.
The outbreak is currently affecting the area known as Triple Frontera
(Triple Borderline). In Paraguay 112 cases of dengue fever have been
detected, as well as 480 suspected cases, while in Foz de Iguazu (Brazil),
31 dengue fever cases have been reported, and there are 150 suspected cases.
In the past few months, the presence of the dengue fever mosquito vector
has increasingly been reported in different zones in Argentina, and so far
there are 25r confirmed cases and 13 suspected cases.
The last outbreak of dengue fever was reported in 2000, consisting of 242
cases in Formosa Province and 218 cases in Misiones Province.
According to World Health Organization (WHO), dengue is one of the main
health problems in the world, since both case figures and mortality rates
are increasing.
It is thought that currently more than 2 billion people live in areas
exposed to dengue fever transmission.
